 argues that while pregnant women in Mexico today have options that were unavailable just over a decade ago, they are also subject to the expanded reach of the Mexican state and the Catholic Church over their bodies and reproductive lives. By analyzing the moral politics of clinical encounters in Mexico City's public abortion program, Lawful Sins offers a critical account of the relationship among reproductive rights, gendered citizenship, and public healthcare. With timely insights on global struggles for reproductive justice, Singer reorients prevailing perspectives that approach abortion rights as a hallmark of women's citizenship in liberal societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAbortionxGovernment policyzMexico. 0aAbortionxSocial aspectszMexico. 0aReproductive rightszMexico. 0aWomenzMexicoxSocial conditions. 0aWomen's rightszMexico. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aMexico.  aabortion.  aclinical encounters.  agender.  aobstetric violence.  apublic health.  areproductive governance.  areproductive justice.  areproductive rights.  awomen’s health.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363148940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631489423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631489/original  a978-3-11